{{pp-pc1}}
{{Same-sex unions}}
{{Use American English|date=July 2015}}  
{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}
'''Same-sex marriage in the United States''' expanded from one state in 2004 to all fifty states in 2015 through various state court rulings, state legislation, direct popular votes, and federal court rulings. [[Same-sex marriage]] is also referred to as '''gay marriage''', while the political status in which the marriages of same-sex couples and the marriages of opposite-sex couples are recognized as equal by the law is referred to as '''marriage equality'''.

Civil rights campaigning in support of marriage without distinction as to sex or sexual orientation began in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 16, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1972, the now overturned ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' saw the U.S. Supreme Court decline to become involved.<ref name="Gumbel">{{cite news |last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|title=The Great Undoing?|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/06/20/great-undoing|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> The issue became prominent from around 1993, when the [[Supreme Court of Hawaii]] ruled in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]'' that it was unconstitutional under the [[Constitution of Hawaii|state constitution]] for the state to abridge marriage on the basis of sex. That ruling led to federal and state actions to explicitly abridge marriage on the basis of sex in order to prevent the marriages of same-sex couples from being recognized by law, the most prominent of which was [[Defense of Marriage Act|DOMA]]. In 2003, the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court]] ruled in ''[[Goodridge v. Department of Public Health]]'' that it was unconstitutional under the [[Constitution of Massachusetts|state constitution]] for the state to abridge marriage on the basis of sex. From 2004 through to 2015, as [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|the tide of public opinion]] continued to move towards support of same-sex marriage, various state court rulings, state legislation, direct popular votes ([[referendum]]s and [[initiative]]s), and federal court rulings established same-sex marriage in 36 states.

During the first decade of the 21st century, gay marriage received vocal support from such figures as civil rights leader [[Coretta Scott King]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-g-long/coretta-scott-king_b_2592049.html|title=Coretta’s Big Dream: Coretta Scott King on Gay Rights|work=[[HuffPost]]|author=Michael Long|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/03/coretta-scott-king-extract|title='I am not a symbol, I am an activist': the untold story of Coretta Scott King|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Jeanne Theoharis|date=February 3, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/02/coretta-scott-king/552557/|title=Coretta Scott King and the Civil-Rights Movement's Hidden Women|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Jeanne Theoharis|date=February 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref> and [[Mildred Loving]], plaintiff in the 1967 case that had made [[Interracial marriage in the United States|interracial marriage]] legal nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/mildred-loving-endorses-marriage-equality-for-same-sex-couples/|title=Mildred Loving Endorses Marriage Equality for Same-Sex Couples|publisher=[[American Constitution Society]]|date=June 15, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/daily-dish/archive/2007/06/mildred-loving-40-years-later/227582/|title=Mildred Loving, 40 Years Later|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> In 2011, [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|national public support for same-sex marriage]] rose above 50% for the first time.<ref name="news.gallup.com">{{cite web|title=For First Time, Majority of Americans Favor Legal Gay Marriage|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/147662/first-time-majority-americans-favor-legal-gay-marriage.aspx|website=[[Gallup (company)|Gallup]]|date=May 20, 2011}}</ref> In 2012, the [[NAACP]], the leading African-American civil rights organization, declared its support for same-sex marriage and stated that it is a [[civil right]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacp.org/latest/naacp-passes-resolution-in-support-of-marriage-equality/|title=NAACP PASSES RESOLUTION IN SUPPORT OF MARRIAGE EQUALITY|publisher=[[NAACP]]|date=May 20, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.naacp.org/latest/naacp-speaks-out-for-marriage-equality/|title=NAACP SPEAKS OUT FOR MARRIAGE EQUALITY|publisher=[[NAACP]]|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}{{indent}}{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/20/us/politics/naacp-endorses-same-sex-marriage.html|title=In Largely Symbolic Move, N.A.A.C.P. Votes to Endorse Same-Sex Marriage|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref> In 2013, the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] struck down [[Defense of Marriage Act|DOMA]] for violating the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] in the landmark civil rights case of ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', leading to federal recognition of same-sex marriage, with federal benefits for married couples connected to either the state of residence or the state in which the marriage was solemnized. In 2015, [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|national public support for same-sex marriage]] rose to 60% for the first time.<ref name="https">{{cite web|title=Record-High 60% of Americans Support Same-Sex Marriage|url=https://news.gallup.com/poll/183272/record-high-americans-support-sex-marriage.aspx|website=[[Gallup (company)|Gallup]]|date=May 19, 2015}}</ref> That same year, the Supreme Court ruled in the [[List of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]] [[civil rights]] case of ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' that the [[Fundamental rights in the United States|fundamental right]] of same-sex couples to marry on the same terms and conditions as opposite-sex couples, with all the accompanying rights and responsibilities, is guaranteed by both the [[Due Process Clause]] and the [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].

The most prominent supporters of same-sex marriage are human rights and civil rights organizations as well as the medical and scientific communities, while the most prominent opponents are religious groups. The ruling of the Supreme Court in ''Obergefell'' occurred following decades of consistently rising [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|national public support for same-sex marriage in the United States]], with support continuing to rise thereafter.

A [[#Child suicide|study of nationwide data from January 1999 to December 2015]] revealed that the establishment of same-sex marriage is associated with a significant reduction in the rate of attempted suicide among children, with the effect being concentrated among children of a minority sexual orientation, resulting in approximately 134,000 fewer children attempting suicide each year in the United States.

The [[United States of America]] is the most populous country in the world to have established same-sex marriage nationwide.

==Public opinion==
{{Main|Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
[[File:Public opinion of same-sex marriage in USA by state.svg|center|thumb|600px|'''Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the [[United States of America]] by state/district/territory:'''
{{legend|#1B4F72|Majority support same-sex marriage — 80 to 89%}}
{{legend|#2874A6|Majority support same-sex marriage — 70 to 79%}}
{{legend|#3498DB|Majority support same-sex marriage — 60 to 69%}}
{{legend|#85C1E9|Majority support same-sex marriage — 50 to 59%}}
{{legend|#AED6F1|Plurality support same-sex marriage — 40 to 49%}}
{{legend|#F5B7B1|Plurality oppose same-sex marriage — 40 to 49%}}
{{legend|#F1948A|Majority oppose same-sex marriage — 50 to 59%}}
{{legend|#DCDCDC|No recent polling data}}]]
[[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States]] has shifted rapidly since polling of the American people regarding the issue first began on an occasional basis in the 1980s and a regular basis in the 1990s, with support having consistently risen while opposition has continually fallen. National support rose above 50% for the first time in 2011 and has not gone below that mark since then. National support rose to 60% for the first time in 2015 and has not gone below that mark since then. Support continues to rise while opposition continues to fall each year, driven in large part by a significant generational gap in support.<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/234866/two-three-americans-support-sex-marriage.aspx|title=Two in Three Americans Support Same-Sex Marriage|work=[[Gallup (company)|Gallup]]|date=May 23, 2018}}</ref>

From 1988 to 2009, support for same-sex marriage increased between 1% and 1.5% per year and accelerated thereafter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Opinion on Same-Sex Marriage Appears to Shift at Accelerated Pace|url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/opinion-on-same-sex-marriage-appears-to/|website=[[FiveThirtyEight]]|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref>

As of 2016, 83% of Americans aged 18–29 support same-sex marriage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Americans' Support for Gay Marriage Remains High, at 61%|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/191645/americans-support-gay-marriage-remains-high.aspx|website=[[Gallup (company)|Gallup]]|date=May 19, 2016}}</ref>

As of 2017, there is majority support for same-sex marriage in 44 states, plurality support in 4 states, plurality opposition in 1 state, and majority opposition in 1 state.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|title=PRRI - American Values Atlas|url=http://ava.prri.org/#lgbt/2017/States/lgbt_ssm/2,3,9|website=[[Public Religion Research Institute]]|date=2017}}</ref>

==Debate==
===Support===
In the United States and Canada, professional organizations including the [[American Anthropological Association]], the [[American Academy of Pediatrics]], the [[American Medical Association]], the [[American Academy of Nursing]], the [[American Psychological Association]], the [[American Psychiatric Association]], the [[Canadian Psychological Association]], the [[American Sociological Association]], the [[National Association of Social Workers]], the  [[American Psychoanalytic Association]], the [[American Association for Marriage and Family Therapy]], and the [[American Academy of Family Physicians]] have stated that the scientific evidence supports the following conclusions: homosexuality is a natural and normal human sexuality, sexual orientation cannot be chosen or influenced, gay people form stable and committed relationships that are essentially equivalent to the relationships of heterosexuals, same-sex parents are no less capable than opposite-sex parents to raise children, no civilization or viable social order depends on restricting marriage to heterosexuals, and the children of same-sex couples fare just as well or even better than the children of opposite-sex couples.<ref name="Coghlan">{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Coghlan|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn14146-gay-brains-structured-like-those-of-the-opposite-sex|title=Gay brains structured like those of the opposite sex|work=[[New Scientist]]|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Soh">{{cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/cross-cultural-evidence-for-the-genetics-of-homosexuality/|title=Cross-Cultural Evidence for the Genetics of Homosexuality|last=Soh|first=Debra|date=April 25, 2017|work=[[Scientific American]]|accessdate=June 8, 2018|author-link=Debra W. Soh}}</ref><ref name="Kangassalo">{{cite news|first=Katariina|last=Kangassalo|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/147470491100900402|title=Prenatal Influences on Sexual Orientation: Digit Ratio (2D:4D) and Number of Older Siblings|work=[[Sage Journals]]|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Skorska">{{cite news|first=Malvina|last=Skorska|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10508-014-0454-4|title=Facial Structure Predicts Sexual Orientation in Both Men and Women|work=[[SpringerLink]]|date=December 31, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Li">{{cite news|first=Caixia|last=Li|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0191886916304044|title=The relationship between digit ratio and sexual orientation in a Chinese Yunnan Han population|work=[[ScienceDirect]]|date=May 28, 2016|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Lamanna">{{cite book|author1=Mary Ann Lamanna|author2= Agnes Riedmann|author3= Susan D Stewart|title=Marriages, Families, and Relationships: Making Choices in a Diverse Society|publisher=[[Cengage Learning]]|isbn=1305176898|year=2014|page=82|accessdate=February 11, 2016|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fofaAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|quote=[T]he APA says that sexual orientation is not a choice that can be changed... biological, including genetic or inborn hormonal factors, play a significant role in a person's sexuality ([[American Psychological Association]], 2010).}}</ref><ref name="Frankowski">{{cite journal|doi=10.1542/peds.113.6.1827 |author=Frankowski BL|author2=[[American Academy of Pediatrics]] Committee on Adolescence|title=Sexual orientation and adolescents |journal=[[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]]|volume=113 |issue=6|pages=1827–32 |date=June 2004|pmid=15173519|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/113/6/1827.long}}</ref><ref name="Ama-assn.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/member-groups-sections/glbt-advisory-committee/ama-policy-regarding-sexual-orientation.page|title=AMA Policy Regarding Sexual Orientation|publisher=[[American Medical Association]]|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Pediatrics.aappublications.org">{{cite web|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/118/1/349.full|title=The Effects of Marriage, Civil Union, and Domestic Partnership Laws on the Health and Well-being of Children|publisher=[[American Academy of Pediatrics]]|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2005_SameSexMarriage.pdf|title=Position Statement on Support of Legal Recognition of Same-Sex Civil Marriage|publisher=[[American Psychiatric Association]]|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="aaanet.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.aaanet.org/issues/policy-advocacy/Statement-on-Marriage-and-the-family.cfm?renderforprint=1|title=Statement on Marriage and the Family|publisher=[[American Anthropological Association]]|date=|accessdate=June 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2002_Adoption.pdf|title=Position Statement on Adoption and Co-parenting of Children by Same-sex Couples |publisher=[[American Psychiatric Association]]|year=2002|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="San Diego Gay and Lesbian News">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdgln.com/news/2010/08/11/apa-reaffirms-support-same-sex-marriage|title=The APA reaffirms support for same-sex marriage|work=[[San Diego Gay and Lesbian News]]|date=|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aannet.org/assets/docs/marriage%20equality_7-26%2012f.pdf|title=Support for Marriage Equality|publisher=[[American Academy of Nursing]]|date=July 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cpa2006>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/userfiles/Documents/Marriage%20of%20Same-Sex%20Couples%20Position%20Statement%20-%20October%202006%20(1).pdf|title=Marriage of Same-Sex Couples – 2006 Position Statement Canadian Psychological Association|year=2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419195945/http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/userfiles/Documents/Marriage%20of%20Same-Sex%20Couples%20Position%20Statement%20-%20October%202006%20%281%29.pdf|archivedate=2009-04-19}}</ref><ref name="amici2015">[https://www.supremecourt.gov/ObergefellHodges/AmicusBriefs/14-556_American_Psychological_Association.pdf Brief of the American Psychological Association, Kentucky Psychological Association, Ohio Psychological Association, American Psychiatric Association, American Academy of Pediatrics, American Association for Marriage and Family Therapy, Michigan Association for Marriage and Family Therapy, National Association of Social Workers, National Association of Social Workers Tennessee Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Michigan Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Kentucky Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Ohio Chapter, American Psychoanalytic Association, American Academy of Family Physicians, and American Medical Association as Amici Curiae in Support of Petitioners]</ref><ref name="herek2006">{{cite journal|author=Herek GM |title=Legal recognition of same-sex relationships in the United States: a social science perspective |journal=[[American Psychologist]] |volume=61 |issue=6 |pages=607–21 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16953748 |doi=10.1037/0003-066X.61.6.607 |url=http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/AP_06_pre.PDF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610164736/http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/AP_06_pre.PDF |archivedate=2010-06-10 |df= }}</ref><ref name=stacey2010>{{cite journal|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/123248173/HTMLSTART?CRETRY=1&SRETRY=0|title=How Does the Gender of Parents Matter?|accessdate=26 July 2015|doi=10.1111/j.1741-3737.2009.00678.x|volume=72|journal=[[Journal of Marriage and Family]]|pages=3–22}}</ref><ref name=cpa2005>[http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/UserFiles/Documents/advocacy/brief.pdf Brief presented to the Legislative House of Commons Committee on Bill C38 by the Canadian Psychological Association – June 2, 2005.]</ref><ref name="Davis">{{cite news|first=Annie|last=Davis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/oct/23/children-raised-by-same-sex-parents-do-as-well-as-their-peers-study-shows|title=Children raised by same-sex parents do as well as their peers, study shows|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=October 22, 2017|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Bever">{{cite news|first= Lindsey|last=Bever|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2014/07/07/children-of-same-sex-couples-are-happier-and-healthier-than-peers-research-shows|title=Children of same-sex couples are happier and healthier than peers, research shows|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>

[[Mildred Loving]], the joint plaintiff alongside her husband [[Richard Loving]] in the [[List of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]] [[civil rights]] case of ''[[Loving v. Virginia]]'' in 1967, in which the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] struck down all state bans on [[Interracial marriage in the United States|inter-racial marriage]], issued a statement on the 40th anniversary of the ruling in 2007 that supported "the freedom to marry for all."<ref name="American Constitution Society">{{cite web|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/mildred-loving-endorses-marriage-equality-for-same-sex-couples/|title=Mildred Loving Endorses Marriage Equality for Same-Sex Couples|publisher=[[American Constitution Society]]|date=June 15, 2007|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Douglas Martin">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/daily-dish/archive/2007/06/mildred-loving-40-years-later/227582/|title=Mildred Loving, 40 Years Later|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=June 18, 2007|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name="nytimes.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/06/us/06loving.html|title=Mildred Loving, Who Battled Ban on Mixed-Race Marriage, Dies at 68|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Douglas Martin|date=May 6, 2008|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>

[[Coretta Scott King]], a leader of the [[African-American civil rights movement]] and the widow of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], fought for gay rights, linked the civil rights movement with the LGBT rights movement, and expressed her support for same-sex marriage and publicly denounced attempts to define marriage as the "union of a man and a woman" as a form of "gay bashing".<ref name="Michael Long">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/michael-g-long/coretta-scott-king_b_2592049.html|title=Coretta’s Big Dream: Coretta Scott King on Gay Rights|work=[[HuffPost]]|author=Michael Long|date=January 31, 2013|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Jeanne Theoharis">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/03/coretta-scott-king-extract|title='I am not a symbol, I am an activist': the untold story of Coretta Scott King|work=[[The Guardian]]|author=Jeanne Theoharis|date=February 3, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name="theatlantic.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2018/02/coretta-scott-king/552557/|title=Coretta Scott King and the Civil-Rights Movement’s Hidden Women|work=[[The Atlantic]]|author=Jeanne Theoharis|date=February 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>

The [[NAACP]], the leading African-American civil rights organization, has pledged its support for gay rights and same-sex marriage, stating that they "support marriage equality consistent with equal protection under the law provided under the Fourteenth Amendment of the United States Constitution" and declaring that same-sex marriage is a [[civil right]].<ref name="NAACP">{{cite web|url=http://www.naacp.org/latest/naacp-passes-resolution-in-support-of-marriage-equality/|title=NAACP PASSES RESOLUTION IN SUPPORT OF MARRIAGE EQUALITY|publisher=[[NAACP]]|date=May 20, 2018|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref><ref name="naacp.org">{{cite web|url=https://www.naacp.org/latest/naacp-speaks-out-for-marriage-equality/|title=NAACP SPEAKS OUT FOR MARRIAGE EQUALITY|publisher=[[NAACP]]|date=April 2, 2013|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name="The New York Times">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/20/us/politics/naacp-endorses-same-sex-marriage.html|title=In Largely Symbolic Move, N.A.A.C.P. Votes to Endorse Same-Sex Marriage|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 19, 2012|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>

The [[Human Rights Campaign]], the largest [[LGBT rights]] organization in the United States, states that "many same-sex couples want the right to legally marry because they are in love — many, in fact, have spent the last 10, 20 or 50 years with that person — and they want to honor their relationship in the greatest way our society has to offer, by making a public commitment to stand together in good times and bad, through all the joys and challenges family life brings."<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/answers-to-questions-about-marriage-equality Human Rights Campaign website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206134235/http://www.hrc.org/resources/entry/answers-to-questions-about-marriage-equality |date=February 6, 2012 }}. Retrieved November 1, 2010.</ref>

Businessman [[Fernando Espuelas]] argues that same-sex marriage should be allowed because same-sex marriage recognizes the civil right of a minority.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/11/06/espuelas.prop.eight/ | publisher=[[CNN]] | title=Commentary: Latinos should see gay marriage a civil right - CNN.com | date=November 7, 2008 | accessdate=May 23, 2010}}</ref>  According to American history scholar [[Nancy Cott]], who rejects alternatives to same-sex marriage (such as [[civil union]]s), "there really is no comparison, because there is nothing that is like marriage except marriage."<ref name="cott">[http://www.afer.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Perry-Vol-1-1-11-10.pdf Direct Examination of Nancy Cott], p. 208. ''Perry v. Schwarzenegger'', No. 09-2292 (N.D. Cal. January 11, 2010). Retrieved December 20, 2011.</ref>

====Role of social media====
Supporters of same-sex marriage successfully utilized [[social media]] websites such as [[Facebook]] to help achieve their aims.<ref>Switzer, Cody. [http://philanthropy.com/article/Inside-the-Human-Rights/138423/ Inside the Human Rights Campaign's Social-Media Success] Philanthropy. April 9, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref><ref>Lipp, Murray. [http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/01/29/comment-the-power-of-online-activism-social-media-in-the-fight-for-lgbt-equality/ The power of online activism and social media in the fight for LGBT equality] Pink News. January 29, 2013. Accessed, April 14, 2013.</ref><ref>Royal, Denis. [http://southfloridagaynews.com/articles/facebook-page-gay-marriage-usa-pushes-for-equality/111659 Facebook Page 'Gay Marriage USA' Pushes for Equality] South Florida Gay News. April 10, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref> Some have argued that the successful use of social media by [[LGBT rights]] organizations played a key role in the defeat of religion-based opposition.<ref>Ferenstein, Gregory [https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/21/how-the-internet-is-erasing-the-religious-rights-political-power/ How The Internet Is Erasing The Religious Right's Political Power] Tech Crunch. March 21, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref>

One of the largest scale uses of social media to mobilize support for same-sex marriage preceded and coincided with the arrival at the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] of high-profile legal cases for [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]] and [[Defense of Marriage Act|DOMA]] in March 2013. The "red equal sign" project started by the [[Human Rights Campaign]] was an electronic campaign primarily based on Facebook that encouraged users to change their profile images to a red equal sign to express support for same-sex marriage.<ref>[http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/slideshow-hrc-logo-memes HRC Logo Memes] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130408223009/http://www.hrc.org/blog/entry/slideshow-hrc-logo-memes |date=April 8, 2013 }} Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref> At the time of the court hearings, an estimated 2.5 million Facebook users changed their profile images to a red equal sign.<ref>Kleinman, Alexis [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/29/red-equal-sign-facebook_n_2980489.html How The Red Equal Sign Took Over Facebook, According To Facebook's Own Data] ''[[HuffPost]]''. March 30, 2013. Retrieved April 14, 2013.</ref>

===Opposition===
Opposition to same-sex marriage is based on the beliefs that homosexuality is unnatural and abnormal, that the recognition of same-sex unions will promote homosexuality in society, and that children are better off when raised by opposite-sex couples.<ref name="thoughtco">{{cite web | url=https://www.thoughtco.com/moral-and-religious-arguments-250095 | title=Common Arguments Against Gay Marriage | date=16 July 2017 | accessdate=26 September 2017 | author=Cline, Austin}}</ref> These claims are refuted by science which shows that homosexuality is a natural and normal human sexuality, that sexual orientation cannot be chosen or influenced, and that the children of same-sex couples fare just as well or even better than the children of opposite-sex couples.<ref name="Coghlan">{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Coghlan|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn14146-gay-brains-structured-like-those-of-the-opposite-sex|title=Gay brains structured like those of the opposite sex|work=[[New Scientist]]|date=June 16, 2008|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Soh">{{cite news|first=Debra|last=Soh|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/cross-cultural-evidence-for-the-genetics-of-homosexuality/|title=Cross-Cultural Evidence for the Genetics of Homosexuality|work=[[Scientific American]]|date=April 25, 2017|accessdate=June 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Kangassalo">{{cite news|first=Katariina|last=Kangassalo|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/full/10.1177/147470491100900402|title=Prenatal Influences on Sexual Orientation: Digit Ratio (2D:4D) and Number of Older Siblings|work=[[Sage Journals]]|date=October 1, 2011|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Skorska">{{cite news|first=Malvina|last=Skorska|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10508-014-0454-4|title=Facial Structure Predicts Sexual Orientation in Both Men and Women|work=[[SpringerLink]]|date=December 31, 2014|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Li">{{cite news|first=Caixia|last=Li|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0191886916304044|title=The relationship between digit ratio and sexual orientation in a Chinese Yunnan Han population|work=[[ScienceDirect]]|date=May 28, 2016|accessdate=August 15, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Lamanna">{{cite book|author1=Mary Ann Lamanna|author2= Agnes Riedmann|author3= Susan D Stewart|title=Marriages, Families, and Relationships: Making Choices in a Diverse Society|publisher=[[Cengage Learning]]|isbn=1305176898|year=2014|page=82|accessdate=February 11, 2016|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fofaAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82|quote=[T]he APA says that sexual orientation is not a choice that can be changed... biological, including genetic or inborn hormonal factors, play a significant role in a person's sexuality ([[American Psychological Association]], 2010).}}</ref><ref name="Frankowski">{{cite journal|doi=10.1542/peds.113.6.1827 |author=Frankowski BL|author2=[[American Academy of Pediatrics]] Committee on Adolescence|title=Sexual orientation and adolescents |journal=[[Pediatrics (journal)|Pediatrics]]|volume=113 |issue=6|pages=1827–32 |date=June 2004|pmid=15173519|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/113/6/1827.long}}</ref><ref name="Ama-assn.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/member-groups-sections/glbt-advisory-committee/ama-policy-regarding-sexual-orientation.page|title=AMA Policy Regarding Sexual Orientation|publisher=[[American Medical Association]]|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Pediatrics.aappublications.org">{{cite web|url=http://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/118/1/349.full|title=The Effects of Marriage, Civil Union, and Domestic Partnership Laws on the Health and Well-being of Children|publisher=[[American Academy of Pediatrics]]|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2005_SameSexMarriage.pdf|title=Position Statement on Support of Legal Recognition of Same-Sex Civil Marriage|publisher=[[American Psychiatric Association]]|date=|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="aaanet.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.aaanet.org/issues/policy-advocacy/Statement-on-Marriage-and-the-family.cfm?renderforprint=1|title=Statement on Marriage and the Family|publisher=[[American Anthropological Association]]|date=|accessdate=June 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psychiatry.org/File%20Library/Advocacy%20and%20Newsroom/Position%20Statements/ps2002_Adoption.pdf|title=Position Statement on Adoption and Co-parenting of Children by Same-sex Couples |publisher=[[American Psychiatric Association]]|year=2002|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name="San Diego Gay and Lesbian News">{{cite web|url=http://www.sdgln.com/news/2010/08/11/apa-reaffirms-support-same-sex-marriage|title=The APA reaffirms support for same-sex marriage|work=[[San Diego Gay and Lesbian News]]|date=|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aannet.org/assets/docs/marriage%20equality_7-26%2012f.pdf|title=Support for Marriage Equality|publisher=[[American Academy of Nursing]]|date=July 2012|accessdate=November 2, 2013}}</ref><ref name=cpa2006>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/userfiles/Documents/Marriage%20of%20Same-Sex%20Couples%20Position%20Statement%20-%20October%202006%20(1).pdf|title=Marriage of Same-Sex Couples – 2006 Position Statement Canadian Psychological Association|year=2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419195945/http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/userfiles/Documents/Marriage%20of%20Same-Sex%20Couples%20Position%20Statement%20-%20October%202006%20%281%29.pdf|archivedate=2009-04-19}}</ref><ref name="amici2015">[https://www.supremecourt.gov/ObergefellHodges/AmicusBriefs/14-556_American_Psychological_Association.pdf Brief of the American Psychological Association, Kentucky Psychological Association, Ohio Psychological Association, American Psychiatric Association, American Academy of Pediatrics, American Association for Marriage and Family Therapy, Michigan Association for Marriage and Family Therapy, National Association of Social Workers, National Association of Social Workers Tennessee Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Michigan Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Kentucky Chapter, National Association of Social Workers Ohio Chapter, American Psychoanalytic Association, American Academy of Family Physicians, and American Medical Association as Amici Curiae in Support of Petitioners]</ref><ref name="herek2006">{{cite journal|author=Herek GM |title=Legal recognition of same-sex relationships in the United States: a social science perspective |journal=[[American Psychologist]] |volume=61 |issue=6 |pages=607–21 |date=September 2006 |pmid=16953748 |doi=10.1037/0003-066X.61.6.607 |url=http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/AP_06_pre.PDF |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610164736/http://psychology.ucdavis.edu/rainbow/html/AP_06_pre.PDF |archivedate=2010-06-10 |df= }}</ref><ref name=stacey2010>{{cite journal|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/123248173/HTMLSTART?CRETRY=1&SRETRY=0|title=How Does the Gender of Parents Matter?|accessdate=26 July 2015|doi=10.1111/j.1741-3737.2009.00678.x|volume=72|journal=[[Journal of Marriage and Family]]|pages=3–22}}</ref><ref name=cpa2005>[http://www.cpa.ca/cpasite/UserFiles/Documents/advocacy/brief.pdf Brief presented to the Legislative House of Commons Committee on Bill C38 by the Canadian Psychological Association – June 2, 2005.]</ref><ref name="Davis">{{cite news|first=Annie|last=Davis|url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/oct/23/children-raised-by-same-sex-parents-do-as-well-as-their-peers-study-shows|title=Children raised by same-sex parents do as well as their peers, study shows|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=October 22, 2017|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name="Bever"/>

Opponents of same-sex marriage include conservative religious groups such as [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], the [[Catholic Church]] (represented by the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]]), and the [[Southern Baptist Convention]], all of which desire for marriage to remain restricted to opposite-sex marriages.

The funding of the amendment referendum campaigns has been an issue of great dispute. Both judges<ref name="boston">[http://bangordailynews.com/2012/02/01/news/state/anti-gay-marriage-group-loses-maine-list-appeal/ Anti-gay marriage group loses Maine appeal to prevent release of its donor list]. David Sharp, Associated Press, January 31, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jurist.org/forum/2012/01/joshua-douglas-citizens-united.php|title=Campaign Finance After Two Years of Citizens United, Josh Douglas of the University of Kentucky College of Law, January 21, 2012|publisher=Jurist.org|date=January 21, 2012|accessdate=May 19, 2012}}</ref> and the IRS<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/13/business/13gift.html |title=I.R.S. Moves to Tax Gifts to Groups Active in Politics |work=The New York Times |author=Stephanie Strom |date=May 12, 2011}}</ref> have ruled that it is either questionable or illegal for campaign contributions to be shielded by anonymity.

===Politicians and media figures===
[[File:Robin Roberts interviewing Barack Obama.jpg|right|thumb|300px|President [[Barack Obama]] interviewed by [[Robin Roberts (newscaster)|Robin Roberts]] of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''[[Good Morning America]]'', at the [[White House]], May 9, 2012.]]
[[File:Celebrating a new America -lovewins 58242 (18588276403).jpg|thumb|right|300px|The [[White House]], illuminated in rainbow colors, on the evening of the ''Obergefell'' ruling, June 26, 2015.]]
[[Social policy of Barack Obama#Same-sex marriage|Barack Obama's views on same-sex marriage]] varied over the course of his political career and became more consistently supportive of [[same-sex marriage]] rights over time. In the 1990s, he had supported same-sex marriage while campaigning for the [[Illinois Senate]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/01/15/report-obama-changed-view-gay-marriage/|title=Report: Obama Changed His View on Gay Marriage |publisher=Fox News |date=April 7, 2010|accessdate=June 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name="huffingtonpost.com">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/01/13/obama-once-supported-same_n_157656.html|title=Obama Once Supported Same-Sex Marriage 'Unequivocally'|publisher=The Huffington Post |date= January 13, 2009|accessdate=December 20, 2011|first=Jason |last=Linkins}}</ref> During the 2008 presidential campaign, he was opposed to [[same-sex marriage]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2009/0512/obama-and-miss-california-aligned-on-same-sex-marriage |title=Obama and Miss California aligned on same-sex marriage?|work=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]|date=May 12, 2009 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> but he also opposed the 2008 [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|California referendum]] that aimed at reversing a court ruling establishing same-sex marriage there.<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael D.|last=Shear|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/05/AR2010080502211.html|title=President Obama's beliefs meet his policy|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=August 5, 2010|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, he opposed two opposing federal legislative proposals that would have banned or established same-sex marriage nationally, stating that each state had to decide the issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2009/jan/13/gay-supporters-petition-obama-repeal-doma/|title=Gay Supporters Petition Obama to Repeal DOMA|date=January 13, 2009|accessdate=June 24, 2009|first=Penny|last=Paterson|newspaper=[[Santa Barbara Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Eleveld|first=Kerry |title=White House Responds to Iowa|newspaper=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=April 3, 2009|url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid77464.asp|accessdate=September 28, 2014}}</ref> In December 2010, he expressed support for [[civil union]]s with rights equivalent to marriage and for federal recognition of same-sex relationships. He opposed a federal constitutional amendment to ban same-sex marriage.<ref name=whitehouse>{{cite web|title= Civil Rights|url= http://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/civil-rights/|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20091026043205/http://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/civil-rights|dead-url= yes|archive-date= October 26, 2009|publisher= The White House|accessdate= October 3, 2009|df= mdy-all}}</ref> He also stated that his position on same-sex marriage was "evolving" and that he recognized that [[civil union]]s from the perspective of same-sex couples was "not enough".<ref name="wapo">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/23/AR2010122301859.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|title=Obama says his views on same-sex marriage are evolving|accessdate=January 5, 2011|first=Perry|last=Bacon, Jr.|date=December 23, 2010}}</ref> On May 9, 2012, President Obama became the first sitting president to support [[same-sex marriage]]. He still said the legal question belonged to the states.<!---<ref name="obamasupport-ABCNews" />---><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-05-09/news/sns-rt-us-usa-campaign-obama-gaymarriagebre84818y-20120509_1_gay-marriage-civil-unions-lesbian-couples |title=Same-sex couples should be able to marry: Obama|first=Jeff|last=Mason |work=Chicago Tribune|date=May 9, 2012|accessdate=March 20, 2013}}</ref> In October 2014, Obama told an interviewer that his view had changed:
{{quote|author=President [[Barack Obama]], on the matter of same-sex marriage as a constitutional question|text=''Ultimately, I think the [[Equal Protection Clause]] does guarantee same-sex marriage in all fifty states. But, as you know, courts have always been strategic. There have been times where the stars were aligned and the Court, like a thunderbolt, issues a ruling like [[Brown v. Board of Education]], but that's pretty rare. And, given the direction of society, for the Court to have allowed the process to play out the way it has may make the shift less controversial and more lasting.''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toobin|first1=Jeffrey|title=The Obama Brief|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/10/27/obama-brief |work=The New Yorker|accessdate=October 20, 2014|date=October 27, 2014}}</ref>}}

Shortly after winning the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 election]], President [[Donald Trump]] said he's "fine" with same-sex marriage and believes it to be settled law: "It's law. It was settled in the Supreme Court. I mean, it's done."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/gop-president-elect-donald-trump-sex-marriage-settled/story?id=43513067 |title=GOP President-Elect Donald Trump Says Same-Sex Marriage Is 'Settled' Law |publisher=ABC News |date=November 13, 2016}}</ref> This somewhat contrasted with a previous statement he made in June 2015, after ''Obergefell v. Hodges'', in which he said he's personally for "traditional marriage" and that he believed same-sex marriage should be left to the states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/transcript/2015/07/05/donald-trump-punching-back.html|title=Donald Trump punching back|date=July 5, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In that same statement, however, Trump admitted that overturning ''Obergefell'' is not realistic. Several of his federal appointments have also, subsequently, announced they will uphold same-sex marriage and enforce the Supreme Court ruling, while still being personally against same-sex marriage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/sessions-says-he-will-enforce-gay-marriage-decision/article/2611387|title=Sessions says he will enforce gay-marriage decision|first=Susan|last=Crabtree|publisher=}}</ref> namely Attorney General [[Jeff Sessions]] and Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/betsy-devos-supports-same-sex-marriage-spokesman-says|title=Betsy DeVos Supports Same-Sex Marriage, Spokesman Says|publisher=}}</ref>

Former presidents [[Bill Clinton]],<ref>{{cite news|date=May 5, 2011|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/onpolitics/post/2011/05/bill-clinton-endorses-gay-marriage-in-new-york-/|title=Bill Clinton endorses gay marriage in New York|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=June 26, 2012}}</ref> [[Jimmy Carter]]<ref>{{cite news|date=March 19, 2012|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/03/19/president-jimmy-carter-bible-book_n_1349570.html|title=President Jimmy Carter Authors New Bible Book, Answers Hard Biblical Questions|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 26, 2012|first=Paul|last=Raushenbush}}</ref> and Barack Obama, former vice presidents [[Dick Cheney]],<ref>{{cite news|date=September 13, 2011|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/09/13/dick-cheney-gay-marriage_n_960874.html|title=Dick Cheney On Gay Marriage: "I Certainly Don't Have Any Problem With It|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 26, 2012|first=Timothy|last=Stenovec}}</ref> [[Al Gore]],<ref>{{cite web|date=January 17, 2008|url=http://current.com/items/88817757_gay-men-and-women-should-have-the-same-rights.htm|title=Al Gore: 'Gay men and women should have the same rights{{'-}}|publisher=[[Current TV]]|accessdate=July 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091129220957/http://current.com/items/88817757_gay-men-and-women-should-have-the-same-rights.htm|archive-date=November 29, 2009|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Walter Mondale]],<ref name="Mondale">{{cite web|last=Mondale|first=Walter|title=Mondale and Dukakis Back Marriage Equality|publisher=[[ThinkProgress]]|date=May 16, 2013|url=http://thinkprogress.org/lgbt/2013/05/16/2021841/mondale-dukakis-back-marriage-equality/?mobile=nc|accessdate=June 20, 2013}}</ref> and [[Joe Biden]] have voiced their support for same-sex marriage, as have former first ladies [[Laura Bush]],<ref>Wing, Nick. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/05/13/laura-bush-gay-marriage-s_n_574731.html Laura Bush: Gay Marriage Should Be Legal, Abortion Should Remain Legal (VIDEO)]. ''The Huffington Post''. May 13, 2011. Retrieved March 27, 2013.</ref> [[Hillary Clinton]],<ref>Wing, Nick. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/18/hillary-clinton-gay-marriage_n_2900557.html Hillary Clinton Announces Support For Gay Marriage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322020800/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/18/hillary-clinton-gay-marriage_n_2900557.html |date=March 22, 2013 }}. ''The Huffington Post''. March 18, 2013. Retrieved March 27, 2013.</ref> [[Michelle Obama]]<ref>[https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/us-first-lady-michelle-obama-why-she-supports-gay-marriage010612/ US First Lady Michelle Obama on why she supports gay marriage] ''Gay Star News''</ref> and [[Nancy Reagan]].<ref>[http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2013/04/17/nancy-reagan-supports-same-sex-marriage-says-daughter-patti-davis/ Nancy Reagan supports same-sex marriage says daughter Patti Davis] ''Pink News''</ref> Former President [[George H. W. Bush]] and his wife former First Lady [[Barbara Bush]] have served as witnesses to a same-sex wedding, but neither has publicly stated whether this means they support same-sex marriage in general;<ref>{{cite news|publisher=The Washington Post|url=http://m.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/wp/2013/09/25/george-h-w-bush-is-witness-at-same-sex-marriage-in-maine/ |date=September 25, 2013|accessdate=March 17, 2014|title=George H.W. Bush is Witness at Same-Sex Marriage in Maine}}</ref> [[George W. Bush]] reportedly offered to officiate the same wedding,<ref>Johnson, Chris. "[http://www.washingtonblade.com/2015/05/24/george-w-bush-sought-to-officiate-same-sex-wedding-report/ George W. Bush sought to officiate same-sex wedding: report]." Washington Blade. May 24, 2015. Retrieved 2015-05-25.</ref> but has similarly not made a public statement regarding his position on the issue (as president, he was opposed). Fifteen [[U.S. senators]] announced their support in the spring of 2013.<ref>Wilson, Chris. [https://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/same-sex-marriage-senate-endorsement-tracker-154748412--politics.html The same-sex marriage Senate endorsement tracker]. Yahoo! News. Updated June 19, 2013. Retrieved June 27, 2013.</ref> By April 2013, a majority of the Senate had expressed support for same-sex marriage.<ref name="Majority of Senators">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Sunlen|title=Majority of Senate Supports Same Sex Marriage |url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2013/04/another-gop-senator-endorses-same-sex-marriage/|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=ABC News|date=April 2, 2013}}</ref> Senator [[Rob Portman]] of Ohio became the first sitting Republican senator to endorse same-sex marriage in March 2013,<ref>Stein, Sam. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/25/rob-portman-gay-marriage_n_2947796.html Rob Portman's Gay Marriage Conversion Explained By His Son]. ''The Huffington Post''. March 25, 2013. Retrieved June 26, 2013.</ref> followed by Senator [[Mark Kirk]] of Illinois in April,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/republican-sen-mark-kirk-endorses-marriage-equality |first=Andrew|last= Kaczynski |accessdate=September 28, 2014|title=Republican Sen. Mark Kirk Endorses Marriage Equality |date=April 2, 2013 |publisher=Buzzfeed}}</ref> Senator [[Lisa Murkowski]] of Alaska in June,<ref name="Murkowski">{{cite news|last=Burgess|first=Everett |title=Lisa Murkowski Endorses Same Sex Marriage|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2013/06/lisa-murkowski-gay-marriage-stance-93047.html|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=Politico|date=June 19, 2013}}</ref> and Senator [[Susan Collins]] of Maine a year later.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moretto|first=Mario|title=Susan Collins becomes fourth GOP senator to publicly support same-sex marriage|url=http://bangordailynews.com/2014/06/25/politics/elections/susan-collins-i-support-same-sex-marriage/|work=Bangor Daily News|accessdate=June 25, 2014|date=June 25, 2014}}</ref>

Politicians who have notably opposed same-sex marriage have included [[Rick Santorum]], [[Mike Huckabee]], and [[Sarah Palin]].

Prominent politicians who have shifted from opposing to supporting same-sex marriage include President [[Barack Obama]], Republican Senator [[Rob Portman]], and Republican Representative [[Bob Barr]] (the author of the 1996 [[Defense of Marriage Act]]).

In an interview on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'' in August 2010, when [[Glenn Beck]] was asked if he "believe(s) that gay marriage is a threat to [this] country in any way", he stated, "No I don't. ... I believe that [[Thomas Jefferson]] said: 'If it neither breaks my leg nor picks my pocket what difference is it to me?{{' "}}<ref>Elizabeth Tenety, "[http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/undergod/2010/08/glenn_beck_gay_marriage_advocate.html Glenn Beck, Gay Marriage Advocate?]", ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 12, 2010. Retrieved October 31, 2010.</ref><ref>''Talkers Magazine'', {{cite web |url=http://talkers.com/online/?p=3774 |title="2010 Talkers 250" |accessdate=2011-01-31 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130043748/http://talkers.com/online/?p=3774 |archivedate=January 30, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref>

==History==
{{Main|History of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
{{See also|Timeline of same-sex marriage in the United States}}
[[File:Wedding in New Orleans, November 11, 2017.jpg|thumb|right|300px|A newlywed same-sex couple celebrate their marriage in the United States.]]
Civil rights campaigning in support of marriage without distinction as to sex or sexual orientation began in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 16, 2015|accessdate=April 6, 2018}}</ref> In 1972, the now overturned ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' saw the U.S. Supreme Court decline to become involved.<ref name="Gumbel">{{cite news |last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|title=The Great Undoing?|url=http://www.advocate.com/news/2009/06/20/great-undoing|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> The issue became prominent from around 1993, when the [[Supreme Court of Hawaii]] ruled in ''[[Baehr v. Miike|Baehr v. Lewin]]'' that it was unconstitutional under the [[Constitution of Hawaii|state constitution]] for the state to abridge marriage on the basis of sex. That ruling led to federal and state actions to explicitly abridge marriage on the basis of sex in order to prevent the marriages of same-sex couples from being recognized by law, the most prominent of which was [[Defense of Marriage Act|DOMA]]. In 2003, the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court]] ruled in ''[[Goodridge v. Department of Public Health]]'' that it was unconstitutional under the [[Constitution of Massachusetts|state constitution]] for the state to abridge marriage on the basis of sex. From 2004 through to 2015, as [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|the tide of public opinion]] continued to move towards support of same-sex marriage, various state court rulings, state legislation, direct popular votes ([[referenda]] and [[initiative]]s), and federal court rulings established same-sex marriage in 36 states.

In 2004, [[Coretta Scott King]], a leader of the [[African-American civil rights movement]] and the widow of [[Martin Luther King Jr.]], expressed her support for same-sex marriage and publicly denounced attempts to define marriage as the "union of a man and a woman" as a form of "gay bashing".<ref name="Michael Long"/><ref name="Jeanne Theoharis"/><ref name="theatlantic.com"/> In 2007, [[Mildred Loving]], the joint plaintiff alongside her husband [[Richard Loving]] in the 1967 landmark civil rights case of ''[[Loving v. Virginia]]'' in which the Supreme Court of the United States struck down all state bans on [[Interracial marriage in the United States|inter-racial marriage]], expressed her support for same-sex marriage and compared it to inter-racial marriage.<ref name="American Constitution Society"/><ref name="Douglas Martin"/><ref name="nytimes.com"/> In 2011, [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|national public support for same-sex marriage]] rose above 50% for the first time.<ref name="news.gallup.com"/> In 2012, the [[NAACP]], the leading African-American civil rights organization, declared its support for same-sex marriage and stated that it is a [[civil right]].<ref name="NAACP"/><ref name="naacp.org"/><ref name="The New York Times"/> In 2013, the Supreme Court of the United States struck down [[Defense of Marriage Act|DOMA]] for violating the [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] in the landmark civil rights case of ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', leading to federal recognition of same-sex marriage, with federal benefits for married couples connected to either the state of residence or the state in which the marriage was solemnized. In 2015, [[Public opinion of same-sex marriage in the United States|national public support for same-sex marriage]] rose to 60% for the first time.<ref name="https"/> In 2015, the Supreme Court of the United States ruled in the [[List of landmark court decisions in the United States|landmark]] [[civil rights]] case of ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' that the [[Fundamental rights in the United States|fundamental right]] of same-sex couples to marry on the same terms and conditions as opposite-sex couples, with all the accompanying rights and responsibilities, is guaranteed by both the [[Due Process Clause]] and the [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]].

==Legal issues==
[[File:Same-sex marriage in San Francisco City Hall 20080617.jpg|thumb|size=300px|right|The wedding of a same-sex couple being performed in [[San Francisco]] [[San Francisco City Hall|City Hall]] in June 2008.]]
{{See also|Same-sex marriage legislation in the United States}}

The legal issues surrounding [[same-sex marriage]] in the United States are determined by the nation's [[federalism|federal]] system of government, in which the [[Status (law)|status]] of a person, including marital status, is determined in large measure by the individual states. Prior to 1996, the federal government did not define marriage; any marriage recognized by a [[U.S. state|state]] was recognized by the federal government, even if that marriage was not recognized by one or more states, as was the case until 1967 with [[Interracial marriage in the United States|interracial marriage]], which some states [[anti-miscegenation laws|banned by statute]].

Prior to 2004, [[same-sex marriage]] was not performed or recognized in any [[List of states and territories of the United States|U.S. jurisdiction]], but subsequently began to be performed and recognized by law in different jurisdictions through legislation, court rulings,<ref name="Adams & Crary March 11, 2009">Glenn Adams and David Crary, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8789627 "Maine voters reject gay-marriage law"], November 4, 2009</ref> tribal council rulings,<ref name="LittleTraverseBayBand">{{cite news|last=Houston|first=Sonya|title=Tribe marries same-sex couple but state won't recognize it|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/03/17/politics/michigan-same-sex-marriage/index.html?hpt=hp_c5|accessdate=March 18, 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=March 17, 2013}}</ref> and popular referenda.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbcpolitics.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/07/14978747-for-first-time-voters-back-gay-marriage-in-statewide-votes?lite|title=For first time, voters back gay marriage in statewide votes|publisher=NBC News|date=|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usnews.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/02/01/10294578-washington-state-senate-approves-same-sex-marriage-bill|title=Washington State Senate approves same-sex marriage|publisher=MSNBC|date=February 1, 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202041745/http://usnews.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2012/02/01/10294578-washington-state-senate-approves-same-sex-marriage-bill|archivedate=February 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name="The Keweenaw Report">{{cite web|url=http://www.keweenawreport.com/news/kbic-council-shake-up-casino-plan-rejected/|title=KBIC Council Shake-Up; Casino Plan Rejected |publisher=The Keweenaw Report |date=December 14, 2014 |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>

The Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' ended all inter-state legal complications surrounding same-sex marriage, as it orders states to both perform the marriages of same-sex couples and to recognize the marriages of same-sex couples performed in other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/06/gay-marriage-supreme-court-decision-119463.html|title=Supreme Court gay marriage decision: Full text of Obergefell ruling|newspaper=Politico|date=June 26, 2015}}</ref>

===Federal law===
According to the federal government's [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) in 2004, [[Rights and responsibilities of marriages in the United States|more than 1,138 rights and protections]] are conferred to U.S. citizens upon marriage by the federal government; areas affected include [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]] benefits, veterans' benefits, health insurance, [[Medicaid]], hospital visitation, estate taxes, retirement savings, pensions, [[family leave]], and immigration law.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d04353r.pdf|title=2004 updated report of the GAO|format=PDF |date=January 23, 2004|publisher=GAO|accessdate=December 20, 2011}}</ref>

Since July 9, 2015, married same-sex couples throughout the United States have equal access to all the federal benefits that married opposite-sex couples have.<ref name="lynch">{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-lynch-announces-federal-marriage-benefits-available-same-sex-couples|title=Attorney General Lynch Announces Federal Marriage Benefits Available to Same-Sex Couples Nationwide|date=July 9, 2015|publisher=Department of Justice|author=Loretta Lynch|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110003040/https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-lynch-announces-federal-marriage-benefits-available-same-sex-couples|archivedate=10 November 2016}}</ref>

The ''[[Defense of Marriage Act]]'' (DOMA) was enacted in 1996. DOMA's Section 2 says that no state needs to recognize the legal validity of a same-sex relationship even if recognized as marriage by another state. It purports to relieve a state of its reciprocal obligation to honor the laws of other states as required by the Constitution's [[full faith and credit clause]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wermiel|first1=Stephen|title=SCOTUS for law students: The Defense of Marriage Act and the Constitution|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2012/03/scotus-for-law-students-the-defense-of-marriage-act-and-the-constitution-sponsored-by-bloomberg-law/|accessdate=September 23, 2014|publisher=SCOTUSblog |date=March 23, 2012}}</ref> Even before DOMA, however, states sometimes refused to recognize a marriage from another jurisdiction if it was counter to its "strongly held public policies".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wolff|first1=Tobias Barrington|title=DOMA Repeal and the Truth About Full Faith & Credit |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/tobias-barrington-wolff/doma-repeal-and-the-truth_b_905484.html |accessdate=September 23, 2014|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=July 21, 2011}}</ref> Most lawsuits that seek to require a state to recognize a marriage established in another jurisdiction argue on the basis of [[equal protection clause|equal protection]] and [[due process clause|due process]], not the full faith and credit clause.{{efn|Among many examples: (1) the U.S. District Court ruling in ''[[Bourke v. Beshear]]'', which required Kentucky to recognize same-sex marriages from Canada and several U.S. states, was decided on equal protection grounds alone. The plaintiffs claimed that Kentucky's ban violated the full faith and credit clause, but the court found it unnecessary to address that argument.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/206724639/GREGORY-BOURKE-et-al-V-STEVE-BESHEAR-et-al |title=Memorandum Opinion, ''Bouke v. Beshear''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Western District of Kentucky |date=February 12, 2014}}</ref> and (2) the plaintiffs in ''[[Robicheaux v. Caldwell]]'', who sought Louisiana's recognition of their out-of-state marriages, argued only on the basis of equal protection and due process. One of the Louisiana statutes they challenged made clear the state's assertion of its right to deny recognition to the legal act of another state: "A purported marriage between persons of the same sex violates a ''strong public policy'' of the state of Louisiana". (emphasis added)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/238549858/2-13-cv-05090-131 |title=Order and Reasons, ''Robicheaux v. Caldwell''|publisher= U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of Louisiana |date=September 3, 2014}}</ref>}}

DOMA's Section 3 defined marriage for the purposes of federal law as a union of one man and one woman.<ref>{{usc|1|7}}.</ref> It was challenged in the [[United States federal courts|federal courts]]. On July 8, 2010, Judge [[Joseph Louis Tauro|Joseph Tauro]] of the [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts|District Court of Massachusetts]] held that the denial of federal rights and benefits to lawfully married Massachusetts same-sex couples is unconstitutional under the [[equal protection clause]] of the [[United States Constitution|U.S. Constitution]].<ref name="hrc.org">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/09/us/09marriage.html|title=Judge Topples U.S. Rejection of Gay Unions|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 8, 2010|accessdate=June 2, 2011|first1=Abby |last1=Goodnough |first2=John|last2=Schwartz}}</ref> Beginning in 2010, eight federal courts found DOMA Section 3 unconstitutional in cases involving bankruptcy, public employee benefits, estate taxes, and immigration.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.freedomtomarry.org/states/entry/c/doma|title=The Defense of Marriage Act|publisher=Freedom to Marry |accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/05/31/doma-unconstitutional-ruling-appeals-court-boston_n_1559031.html|title=DOMA Ruled Unconstitutional By Federal Appeals Court |last=Lavoie |first=Denise |date=May 31, 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewstates.org/projects/stateline/headlines/defense-of-marriage-act-discriminates-against-gays-federal-court-rules-85899424320|title=Defense of Marriage Act Discriminates Against Gays, Federal Court Rules|last=Malewitz|first=Jim|date=October 18, 2012 |publisher=Pewstates.org|accessdate=October 20, 2012}}</ref> On October 18, 2012, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second Circuit Court of Appeals]] became the first court to hold sexual orientation to be a [[suspect classification|quasi-suspect classification]] and applied [[intermediate scrutiny]] to strike down Section 3 of DOMA as unconstitutional in ''[[Windsor v. United States]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tiven|first=Rachel|title=Edie Wins! Another Ruling Against DOMA, What It Means|url=http://www.immigrationequality.org/2012/10/edie-wins-another-ruling-against-doma-what-it-means/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027051854/http://www.immigrationequality.org/2012/10/edie-wins-another-ruling-against-doma-what-it-means/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=October 27, 2012|publisher=[[Immigration Equality (organization)]]|accessdate=October 23, 2012}}</ref> The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in ''Windsor'' on June 26, 2013, that Section 3 violated the Fifth Amendment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Live Analysis of the Supreme Court Decisions on Gay Marriage |url=http://projects.nytimes.com/live-dashboard/2013-06-26-supreme-court-gay-marriage|accessdate=June 26, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=June 26, 2013}}</ref>{{efn|Other cases that sought review by the U.S. Supreme Court were ''[[Golinski v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Gill v. Office of Personnel Management]]'', ''[[Massachusetts v. United States Department of Health and Human Services]]'', and ''[[Pedersen v. Office of Personnel Management]]''.}}

As a result of the ''Windsor'' decision, married same-sex couples—regardless of domicile—have federal tax benefits (including the ability to file joint federal income tax returns), military benefits, federal employment benefits, and immigration benefits.<ref>{{cite web|title=After DOMA: Military Spousal Benefits|url=https://www.lambdalegal.org/publications/after-doma-military-spouses|website=Lambda Legal|accessdate=19 December 2017|date=15 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Condon|first1=Stephanie|title=One year after DOMA ruling, same-sex couples still face benefits gaps|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/one-year-after-doma-ruling-same-sex-couples-still-face-benefits-gaps/|accessdate=19 December 2017|publisher=CBS News|date=26 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolf|first1=Richard|title=Veterans' same-sex spouses eligible for federal benefits|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/09/04/same-sex-veterans-obama-benefits/2764197/|accessdate=4 September 2013|publisher=USA Today|date=4 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=John Kerry Announces Visa Changes for Same-Sex Couples|url=http://blogs.usembassy.gov/malaysia/2013/08/05/john-kerry-announces-visa-changes-for-same-sex-couples/|publisher=U.S. Embassy Kuala Lumpur|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=August 2, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140322114025/http://blogs.usembassy.gov/malaysia/2013/08/05/john-kerry-announces-visa-changes-for-same-sex-couples/|archivedate=March 22, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In February 2014, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] expanded federal recognition of same-sex marriages to include bankruptcies, prison visits, survivor benefits and refusing to testify against a spouse.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perez |first1=Evan|title=U.S. expands legal benefits, services for same-sex marriages|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/02/08/politics/holder-same-sex-marriage-rights/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=July 26, 2014|date=February 10, 2014}}</ref> Likewise in June 2014, family [[medical leave]] benefits under the ''Family Medical Leave Act 1975'' were extended to married same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chappell |first1=Bill|title=Married Same-Sex Couples To Receive More Federal Benefits |url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2014/06/20/323855724/same-sex-couples-across-u-s-to-receive-broader-benefits |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |publisher=NPR |date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> With respect to [[social security]] and veterans benefits, same-sex married couples are eligible for full benefits from the [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Veterans Affairs]] (VA) and the [[Social Security Administration]] (SSA). Prior to the Supreme Court's ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' on June 26, 2015, the VA and SSA could provide only limited benefits to married same-sex couples living in states where same-sex marriage was not legal.<ref name="Guardian20140620">{{cite news|last1=Glenza|first1=Jessica|title=Federal agencies roll out benefits for married same-sex couples|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/20/same-sex-couples-benefits-expanded-obama-administration |accessdate=July 26, 2014 |newspaper=The Guardian|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Capehart|first1=Jonathan|title=Fix the Social Security discrepancy DOMA left behind |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-partisan/wp/2014/05/09/fix-the-social-security-discrepancy-doma-left-behind/ |accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=The Washington Post|date=May 9, 2014}}</ref> Effective March 27, 2015, the definition of spouse under the ''[[Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993]]''<ref>{{cite news|last1=Forman|first1=Shira|title=DOL Issues Final Rule Amending FMLA Definition of "Spouse" to Include Same-Sex Marriages|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/dol-issues-final-rule-amending-fmla-definition-spouse-to-include-same-sex-marriages|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=Sheppard Mullin Richter & Hampton LLP|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref> includes employees in a same-sex marriage regardless of state of residence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Trotier|first1=Geoffrey S.|title=FMLA "Spouse" Definition Now Includes Same-Sex Spouses and Common-Law Spouses|journal=The National Law Review|date=February 24, 2015|url=http://www.natlawreview.com/article/fmla-spouse-definition-now-includes-same-sex-spouses-and-common-law-spouses|accessdate=February 28, 2015|publisher=von Briesen & Roper, s.c}}</ref> Following the ''Obergefell'' decision, the Justice Department extended all federal marriage benefits to married same-sex couples nationwide.<ref name="lynch"/>

The federal government recognizes the marriages of same-sex couples who married in certain states in which same-sex marriage was legal for brief periods between the time a court order allowed such couples to marry and that court order was stayed, including [[Michigan]]. The federal government also recognized marriages performed in [[Utah]] from December 20, 2013 to January 6, 2014, even while the state didn't. Under similar circumstances, the federal government never took a position on [[Indiana]] or [[Wisconsin]]'s marriages performed in brief periods, though it did recognize them once the respective states announced they would do so. It had not taken a position with respect to similar marriages in [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Chris|title=DOJ pressured to recognize same-sex marriages in 3 states|url=http://www.washingtonblade.com/2014/09/19/doj-pressured-recognize-sex-marriages-3-states/|accessdate=September 24, 2014|work=Washington Blade|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> prior to the ''Obergefell'' decision legalizing and recognizing same-sex marriages in all fifty states.

Opponents of same-sex marriage have worked to prevent individual states from recognizing same-sex unions by attempting to amend the United States Constitution to restrict marriage to heterosexual unions. In 2006, the ''[[Federal Marriage Amendment]]'', which would have prohibited states from recognizing same-sex marriages, was approved by the [[United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary|Senate Judiciary Committee]] on a party-line vote and was debated by the full Senate, but was ultimately defeated in both houses of Congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511145406/http://www.cnn.com/2006/POLITICS/06/07/same.sex.marriage/index.html|title=Senate blocks same-sex marriage ban|publisher=CNN|date=June 7, 2006|archivedate=May 11, 2008|accessdate=July 5, 2006}}</ref> On April 2, 2014, the [[Alabama House of Representatives]] adopted a resolution calling for a [[Convention to propose amendments to the United States Constitution|constitutional convention]] to propose an amendment to ban same-sex marriage nationwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140402/NEWS/304020079/Alabama-House-approves-call-put-same-sex-marriage-ban-U-S-Constitution |title=Alabama House approves call to put same-sex marriage ban in U.S. Constitution |work=Montgomery Advertiser |date=April 2, 2014 |accessdate=April 3, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140412171146/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20140402/NEWS/304020079/Alabama-House-approves-call-put-same-sex-marriage-ban-U-S-Constitution |archivedate=April 12, 2014 }}</ref>

===State and territorial recognition===
{{Further|Same-sex marriage law in the United States by state}}
Same-sex marriages are licensed in and recognized by all U.S. states and [[Same-sex marriage in the District of Columbia|Washington, D.C.]], as well as all U.S. territories except [[LGBT rights in American Samoa|American Samoa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/samesex-marriage-american-samoa-may-be-the-only-territory-in-the-us-where-the-historic-supreme-court-ruling-does-not-apply-10379804.html|title=Same-sex marriage: American Samoa may be the only territory in the US where the historic Supreme Court ruling does not apply|work=The Independent|accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> On July 3, 2015, the Attorney General for American Samoa stated "we are reviewing the opinion [''Obergefell v. Hodges''] and its potential applicability to American Samoa, and will provide comment when it is completed."<ref>[https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/american-samoa-questions-gay-marriage-validity-in-territory/ American Samoa questions gay marriage validity in territory] ''The Seattle Times'', July 10, 2015</ref> On January 6, 2016, Alabama's Chief Justice, [[Roy Moore]], issued a ruling forbidding state officials from issuing marriage licenses to same-sex couples.<ref name="RoyMoore">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/alabama-chief-justice-orders-halt-gay-marriage-n491521|title=Alabama Chief Justice Orders Halt to Gay Marriage|first=Pete|last=Williams|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> The ruling had no effect as all Alabama counties continued either issuing marriage licenses to all couples or not issue licenses at all. In May 2016 Moore was charged with ethics violations by the state Judicial Inquiry Commission for the ruling,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-alabama-gaymarriage-idUSKCN0XY042|title=Alabama's top judge faces ethics charges over gay-marriage order|work=Reuters|date=7 May 2016}}</ref> subsequently being suspended from the bench for the remainder of his term on September 30 of that year.<ref name="almedgrp">{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/birmingham/index.ssf/2016/09/alabama_supreme_court_chief_ju.html|title=Alabama Supreme Court Chief Justice Roy Moore suspended for rest of term|publisher=Alabama Media Group|first=Kent|last=Faulk|date=September 30, 2016|accessdate=September 30, 2016}}</ref>

====Counties not issuing marriage licenses====
[[File:Same-sex marriage in Texas by county, August 2015.png|180px|thumb|As of June 20, 2017, only Irion county (pink) refuses licenses to same-sex couples.<ref name="Ballotpedia">{{cite web|title=Local government responses to Obergefell v. Hodges|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Local_government_responses_to_Obergefell_v._Hodges#tab=Texas|website=ballotpedia.org|date=July 1, 2015 – June 26, 2017}}</ref>]]
[[File:Counties.png|180px|thumb|Counties issuing marriage licenses to all couples (blue) and counties issuing to no one (grey) as of June 2017]]
Officials of nine counties in two states, [[Same-sex marriage in Texas|Texas]] and [[Same-sex marriage in Alabama|Alabama]], are still  unwilling to issue licenses to same-sex couples as of June 2017. Those wishing to marry within the state must travel to another part of the state in order to obtain a license. However, some counties may require at least one person to be a resident of the county in order to receive a marriage license.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://altoday.com/archives/17555-two-years-later-7-alabama-counties-still-not-issuing-marriage-licences-sex-couples|title=2yrs later, 7co. still not issuing same-sex marriage licenses|date=2017-06-29|work=Alabama Today|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US}}</ref>
